column168: ON MAY 1 1985 DURING THE DAILY FACILTY INSPECTION, A DRUM BEING STORED IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT, INSIDE A TRAILER , WAS FOUND TO HAVE DAMPNESS ALONG THE BOTTOM SEAM AND ON THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN. THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AS A FLAMMABLE SOLVENT WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYL (PCB) CONTAMINATION (20,000 PPM). THEREFORE, THE CLEAN UP WAS CONDUCTED WITH SPECIAL PRECAUTIONS. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED INSIDE AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE, ABOUT 4OZ, WAS CLEANED UP AND THE AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED* THEN DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL AND STATE REGULATIONS. * 5-16-85: LAB RESULTS INDICATE AREA WAS COMPLETELY DECONTAMINATED. 5-19-85: THESE MATERIALS INCLUDING SPILL CLEAN UP WILL BE SENT TO: CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, 1550 BALMER RD, MODEL CITY, NY 14107.

I STOPPED AT ASHLAND, VA TRUCK STOP TO CHECK LOAD AND TAKE A BREAK. EVERY- THING WAS OK. WHEN I STOPPED AT LAUREL,MD FACILITY I NOTICED THE TRAILER WA S LEAKING FROM THE REAR. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION I FOUND THE DRUM (020585 MIO -19) TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM WELD. I OVER PACKED THE DRUM AND MADE NOTIFICATION TO AL HARRELL AT 2:AM. THE DRUM WAS SENT ON WITH THE REMAINING LOAD TO THE FINAL DESTINATION FOR DISPOSAL.
